@ChelseaParlett Then we could visualize a random set of 20 trials using geom_tile (the Xs represent ☠️) #rstats https://t.co/CAWyK5UrnA

@ChelseaParlett We can use stat_ecdf to see a player's chances of surviving a game of a particular length

This confirms we can calculate it with the binomial CDF! Player k's chance in an n-step game is pbinom(k - 1, n, .5) #rstats https://t.co/OHFx49MB1g

@ChelseaParlett The chance of player i and player j surviving aren't independent (e.g. if i > j, then if i survives j does as well)

and the ones with `FALSE` are dropped. If in case your logical vector is of smaller length, the elements are recycled to match the corresponding length. So in the above example: `y` is of length 4, so when used as `x[y]`, `y` gets #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:18102021220006]
`NA`. So the output will be `1 NA 5`. #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:18102021220006]

Correct Ans: `1 NA 5`. There are two things to note here. First: Indexing with NA, and Second: Indexing with logicals. When you index with NA, you get NA. When you index with logical vectors, the positions with `TRUE` gets selected #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:18102021220006]

recycled to `(T, F, F, NA, T, F)` and `x` is indexed as `x[c(T, F, F, NA, T, F)]`. Since position `1` and `5` are `TRUE`, those will be returned, the ones with `FALSE` will not be returned and the position which has `NA` will return #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:18102021220006]
